                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;09/30/2003&nbsp;: 01:27:14 AM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> Wow! This is an interesting discussion.<br /><br />Certainly not something I expected to find nestled deep in the rants forum, though I can see why it is with all of the childish name calling and whining that has taken place in some of the posts.<br /><br />We basically have two sides here. They are:<br />1) The side of the people who think what the USA did in Iraq was for "good" reason.<br />2) The side of the people who think what the USA did in Iraq was for "bad" reasons.<br /><br />Each of these sides are convinced that they are right and the other is wrong.<br />They demonstrate this by degrading the other side when something is said that they disagree with, whether it is in the form of offerring facts to prove them wrong or simple name calling as a few have done.<br /><br />Now, instead of taking either of those sides myself, why don't I try to offer a different perspective to all of you who are fighting over this matter?<br /><br />Quote Banez Wright:<br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">As a few people have pointed out, if this was the only factor for us going into Iraq, then we should have done the same to a LOT of other countries in the world.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />Know what? It isn't the only factor.<br />There are many many factors. <br />Too many.<br />More than you will ever know, more than I will ever know, more than ANYONE will ever know.<br />What's the problem here? <br />The problem is that any conclusion you make based on the few simple facts that YOU have is entirely pointless, because without<br />seeing the full picture - the entire equation -you will never really know if things that were done were done for the right reasons.<br /><br />Quote Drexyll:<br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Do you take everything at face value and buy the insinuation without thinking about it? <hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />Thinking about it? What good will that do?<br />You do not have all of the facts, and the facts which you think you DO have are from people and places that you could never prove the validity of by yourself.<br />Any conclusion you can come up with in your head without all of the necessary facts depends on your own personal opinions, which obviously mean nothing conclusive.<br /><br />Quote Banez Wright:<br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">The fact remains that we are there now, that 99% of our population are like sleeping lambs and have no clue what the reality of the situation was when we entered, or even is now.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />I couldn't agree more, except for the fact that you just happen to be one of those sleeping lambs you refer to in your post; as am I, and as is every other person posting here.<br /><br />Quote Drexyll:<br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Where's the troops in Sudan? Rwanda? Cambodia? Why is China one of our largest trading partners? (particularly while we refuse to trade with Cuba). Again, it's hypocrisy.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />Hypocrisy, is it?<br />So many questions here Drexyll.<br />Where are the troops you ask?<br />You don't know, because you don't have all of the facts.<br />You will never have all of the facts. <br />Nobody will have ALL of the facts.<br />And I guarantee you that an average citizen like yourself will never even come close to knowing all of the facts.