                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;09/25/2003&nbsp;: 01:05:02 AM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> Kebkeck,<br /><br />While it seems we agree on some points we have strong differences of al least three spots.<br /><br />First, while 4 months may not seem like a long time we have completed the first wave a site examinations. This search was conducted several hundred investigators and was conducted on more than one hundred sites. These sites were listed by our intelligence services as the most probable to conduct WMD product, manafacture capacity, and research. Nothing was found.<br /><br />We have conducted interviews with the scientists and engineers that were, supposedly, working in the Iraqi weapons program. All, to my knowledge, have denied the existance, in recent years, of a weapons program. (I do concede that a weapons program was in place and operating thru the mid 90s at least.)<br /><br />Further there seems disturbing signals coming from our own government. It upsets me to hear my president say we have found weapons of mass destruction as our president did regard the mobile chemical trucks, but then to read the CIA assessment of them they could not be used to make chemical weapons. <br /><br />The second point I take exception with is your statement regarding "false enlightenment". I was concerned prior to the war that Saddam had an 'active' weapons program that could yield a nuclear device 'with in a year'. I drew this from direct quotes from Wolfowitz(sp?), Cheney, and Rice. All of who stated Saddam had an active WMD program and could deploy a nuclear bomb with a year. We were in no other term spectacularly wrong on this point. <br /><br />My concerns prior to the war were unfounded based on discovered facts after our occupation of Iraq. This is not "false" enlightenment but simply enlightenment. Now we come to learn according Wolfowitz that WMDs were settled on as the best reason to 'sell' a war on Iraq. Our state of enlightenment has increased with each day we spend in Iraq. <br /><br />Lastly you argue that IF our action in Iraq stops an other attack then it is justified. Well we certainly agree on that point! However I do not believe that anyone can reasonably argue how our actions in Iraq could prevent a future attack. In fact, quite the opposite, they guarantee an attack. Not anything as horrific as 9/11 mind you but we are now in a shooting war. A war that has not subsided since May. A war that has killed over 200 Americans and wounded over 1000. If these numbers continue more than 1000 Americans will die in Iraq over the term of the occupation and many thousands will be wounded. The cost to our Nation could reach a quarter trillion and we have no assurances of our success. <br /><br />The loss of life and resources by our occupation of Iraq could easily exceed that lost on 9/11. Such a loss would be justified if it would prevent an attack upon us, such a loss would be justified if Iraq present a viable threat but neither of these are remotely probable. <br /><br /></span></font></td>
