ent/com0303k.asp" target="_blank">http://www.fff.org/comment/com0303k.asp</a></a><br /><br />"It would seem that the only real guideline that the U.S. government uses with respect to dictators is their relative usefulness for doing its bidding. "<br /><br />This sounds right on to me..<br /><br />It is this one that gets me...<br /><br />"And lets not forget Osama bin Laden. The mastermind of the World Trade Center and Pentagon attacks himself once had a close relationship with the U.S. government. During the Soviet occupation of Afghanistan, bin Ladens position in the mujahideen made him and his men prime recipients of American military training and equipment. The U.S. government loved watching Afghan guerillas attack Soviet aircraft. It wasnt so funny when they began targeting Americans. "<br /><br />Throughout this text, the writer correctly points out how we proped up these dictators, but fails to explain the justification for doing so.. that gets convienently left out.. hmm Liberal... ? It isn't important to the writer to explain that, just to point out that we are hypocritical, when in fact I see logic in the thinking behind doing it, yet horrible cleanup once the dirtywork is finished.<br />.<br />.<br />.<br /> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">You know all the history lessons you got as a child never told you about these things, because what would be people be like if they couldnt sleep well at night thinking our country is NOT the <i>good guys</i> when in fact most of the world is afraid of us, or downright hates us.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />My opinion on "why"  we don't learn about things like this is because in the years you learn basic history your hardly ready or interested in learning politics of War, and by the time people do want to learn about these issues, they are going to a college with a 10 - 1 ratio of liberal educa